<DOC><DOCNO> AP890815-0156 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1747EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     08-15 0200</FIRST><SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,200</SECOND><HEAD>US Hopes to Work on Anti-Apartheid Discussions</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-South Africa Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The State Department said Tuesday it hopes toconduct an ``active dialogue'' with the new South African leadershipto press for an end to apartheid, and held out the possibility of aU.S. visit by acting President F.W. de Klerk.   The department declined comment, however, on the resignation ofPresident P.W. Botha, calling it an internal South African affair.   ``We look forward to an active dialogue with the new SouthAfrican government as part of our efforts to promote realnegotiations leading to a non-racial democracy in South Africa,''department spokesman Richard Boucher said.   ``The level of that dialogue will be determined mutually in ourdiscussions with the new government,'' he said.   Asked whether de Klerk would be invited to visit by PresidentGeorge Bush, Boucher said that ``will be determined mutually in ourdiscussions.''   De Klerk, who is expected to be elected president in Septemberballoting, intended to visit the United States this summer andbecome the first South African leader to do so in 30 years. But hepostponed his visit, citing a heavy cammpaign schedule, underpressure from Congress.</TEXT></DOC>